Adding the description of the server infrastructure for Symplectic Elements
Request an OIT Service Account for granting the Digital Science Team access to Symplectic Elements Servers

comments.body: Access granted by OIT this morning; asking the vendor to test and confirm access.

In order to access either server environments, one will first need to access the bastion host `lib200w.princeton.edu`. This must be undertaken using the Microsoft Remote Desktop client:

# macOS
- https://apps.apple.com/us/app/microsoft-remote-desktop/id1295203466?mt=12
# Windows
- https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/how-to-use-remote-desktop-5fe128d5-8fb1-7a23-3b8a-41e636865e8c
# *NIX
- https://github.com/TigerVNC/tigervnc

Using the client distributed using the Apple Store for a brief overview of this process, one finds the following configuration for PCs:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1443986/161774982-8c074545-1d5d-44eb-8213-9f0a515b761b.png)

The configuration for the `lib200w` host is the following, where the account name is `princeton\$NETID` for the NetID of a service account:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1443986/161775370-3d2c8653-9c14-488d-a042-bcc9698076bd.png)

Please be aware that one must be authenticated on the Princeton VPN (https://princeton.service-now.com/service?id=kb_article&sys_id=KB0012373), and that one must ensure that the OIT has explicitly provided authentication privileges for the service account on the bastion host.

A SN@P ticket has been created in order to ensure that the service account for Digital Science can both access the VPN, as well as the `lib200w` bastion host: https://princeton.service-now.com/now/workspace/agent/record/incident/df2613eb8766811012ae43bd0ebb35f0

This functionality already exists if you go to the catalog route rather than the concerns route.

https://github.com/pulibrary/figgy/blob/43a72978a46b7a763218a1af5f2ef57b868215af/app/controllers/catalog_controller.rb#L222-L225

> Presumably if these items are eligible for download we don't need to provide cover pages for these PDFs?

Yes, the main use cases for providing downloads of the original PDFs are all cases where Princeton owns the copyright (concert programs, curatorial notes, etc.) or where the items are clearly fair-use (tables of contents).

> This functionality already exists if you go to the catalog route rather than the concerns route.

Looking at the Ability class, I think this likely means that we need to add some logic to say that PDF source files are downloadable, maybe here: https://github.com/pulibrary/figgy/blob/main/app/models/ability.rb#L274
